[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Java testing approach**\n\nI'm reflecting on whether to use Java's ServiceLoader with a top-level public provider file. It might complicate things if I create a public Scenario interface in a separate file. I should simplify by focusing on just v1 and v2 without adding too many sources. Maybe I could have two separate Gradle Test tasks, but I wonder if that's overkill. The user wanted fewer direct reflection tests, and I'm considering the best way to use class loaders while keeping things simple.\n\n**Considering class structure and testing**\n\nI'm wondering if I should define the v2 class only for the child, so the parent class covers v1 without complications. This way, there'd be no child for v1, but the child can handle v2. Additional reflection is still a concern. However, the parent test could cover v1 through the public API. Using dynamic class loading for the child v2 makes sense since it might simplify testing under native conditions while ensuring the main test still captures v1.\n\n**Evaluating project structure**\n\nI’m considering NativeImageSupport and how to catch errors, trusting that approach. I think adding the source set path might not set in the native context, so I’m exploring alternatives, like a child loader that includes resources under src/test/resources/v2-fixture-classes. \n\nInstead, I might simplify things. The parent would contain both fake v2 and v1, with the child loader blocking v2 while still using v1 classes for testing. I will ensure it loads the necessary dependencies correctly.\n\n**Refining class loading**\n\nI'm working with a child loader that has a parent but prioritizes loading certain classes like org.mozilla.javascript and jline while blocking v2. For the Scenario interface, I might use a static method for running tests instead of relying on reflection. \n\nI could have the child scenario implement java.util.concurrent.Callable and use ServiceLoader for this. To simplify things, I’d make ShellConsoleV1Scenario public, separate it into its own file, and ensure the service provider config is correctly set up in `src/test/resources/META-INF/services`. This should help avoid explicit reflection issues.\n\n**Considering class loading constraints**\n\nI see that I can implement the parent Callable in the child-loaded class since java.util.concurrent is available in the bootstrap class loader, which is great! Now, I need to ensure that the helper class is public and follows the necessary rules. \n\nI’m thinking about setting up the child class loader to exclude certain elements, like the v2 fixtures, which should help in blocking unwanted v2 components effectively. It’s all coming together!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0568128f112b68520169f51e9d315481a09a03a5ce11d48b74\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9R7Q6hTPk7sA61OCTSFXj-RONXgEODvpZ7JUNJBZZFDC9kca8ttPqIJYYQMmyWczdD9X4M6m1GVa-c76HFPGpPQdHt3VawTpy3KqANJCB0-dM3gs10DwYmRtPB28qWk3DL7d2vzUKNOh6I0kOao8F_MArtI_gGhMHjx7lwFIL2WHgp6FeY1IuwaO72NHMNAjBsKy1LihTCk1OPaw8p6_u88sieRhUA2F3L32xtqyiaBNP9a3SGKKa8OUbM4uIPrMt_3mA3TjlMEvFO3s-15lbBfd59kLLjzc-rpu3akfg7YV76PO2OXne0wfjJcGF4sl9Ul4rEM7-iUIsxdOopAOpJz9qTH9CAOSbiKQrBT8xBt9mPss6gok8gjZAvncys5SofmM1Amah3KUvvXcxfX2itQuy2cpAxbi6M8ihGNsXMKNxU-x3DIUTjOyEUB5oe29nLpYCEqFQ3Xoka5USEwbD8wOg4C_iw3JHwKGOWoPuws6B9Q5ScdpRx4auWB2rWozx1tGlas2W6e-xN7ENz037VNQFb4omsORX2vAIW9apOK1k86YQ4ZReg27KhOXXpJSduqdeQnlCkORGcEmiTwWEtb1M96Svj2u6tx_99IaTBq3hUzanfSO4sELzqZyrYc2BQeOpwIscI-nyyAxWt3iW7dB0SrdNn6NGmdNZEpalVNB_FYWyvtE0dRXIlmOyBzk_Wve9_NVOqylx23sA9ee16dDA-4IveAZie1xF1quFjfnBaBZXAhTYoN_ln_DgJBJMMbw13xuoWteR522_NHnUWBjA4BCz-uSnouztkbmbh2gz2PIXXhfXW4bSI3ITWzOC8pxoZX5rspymUhuD-8FaZpD9mraKkLDoA2mi8Oy5deqgIHSqsjsxhNKSNtBecTG-2uelDp43yAy90W9a2ZOlE0qHc9htOU2WoZ1vCTmpD2X-LUyY1KcDERRkQWsru1Gjr562gqImWmUHAUYejwv8P5ARRx-lQ6Y-PHfEkAsTLUVHsrlJUKpwTu8ObILPjg5GMQ4fgox8uZuuzhs0BYSIuiwBJHdYetG